{{Infobox language |name = Bete |states = Bete Town, [[Takum]] Local Government Authority, [[Taraba State]], [[Nigeria]]. |ethnicity = 3,000 [[Bete people (Nigeria)|Bete]] (1992)<ref name=e14>{{e14|BYF}}</ref> |speakers = 50 |date = 1992 |ref = e18 |familycolor=Niger-Congo |fam2=[[Atlantic–Congo]] |fam3=[[Benue–Congo languages|Benue–Congo]] |fam4= [[Plateau languages|Plateau]] |fam5= [[Yukubenic languages|Yukubenic]] |fam6= Bete–Lufu |iso3=byf |glotto=bete1261 |glottorefname=Bete (Jukunoid) }}
The '''Bete''' language of [[Nigeria]] is a nearly extinct language spoken by a small minority of the 3,000 inhabitants of Bete Town, [[Takum]], [[Taraba State]]; its speakers have mostly shifted to [[Jukun Takum language|Jukun Takum]]. It is close to [[Lufu language|Lufu]].
