{{Agri-stub}}

'''Hans Aarnes''' (6 May 1886 &ndash; 25 October 1960) was a [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] [[entrepreneur]], journalist, newspaper editor, magazine editor, [[publisher]] and proponent for the [[Nynorsk language]].
==Early and personal life== Aarnes was born in [[Vatne, Møre og Romsdal]] as the son of farmer Kristen Nilsson Aarnes and Marta Kristensdotter Vestre. He graduated as shipper in 1904, and worked as a seaman, trader and fisher. In 1907 he published the one-act play ''Sundagskveld'', and in 1933 he published the poetry collection ''Kviteburd''. He was married to Gina Villesvik from 1913.<ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Hans Aarnes |encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Hans_Aarnes/utdypning |language=Norwegian|accessdate=24 October 2010}}</ref>
==Career== Aarnes was editor or assistant editor for seven newspapers or magazines.<ref name=nbl/> He edited ''Aarvak'' from 1909 to 1911. He worked for the newspaper ''Norig'' from 1911 to 1913, and edited ''Hardanger'' from 1913. From 1916 to 1920 he worked for the newspaper ''[[Gula Tidend]]'', and for ''[[Bondebladet (newspaper)|Bondebladet]]'' from 1921 to 1923. He edited the newspaper ''[[Agder Tidend]]'' from 1923 to 1932.<ref name=nbl/><ref name=nab>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Aarnes, Hans |first=Severin |last=Eskeland |authorlink=Severin Eskeland |encyclopedia=[[Norsk Allkunnebok]] |volume=10 |year=1966 |editor=[[Arnulv Sudmann|Sudmann, Arnulv]] |editor2=Galdal, Peder |publisher=Fonna Forlag |location=Oslo |language=Norwegian}}</ref>
He established the first education for journalists in Norway, Bladmannaskulen, in 1919,<ref name=snl>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Hans Aarnes |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/Hans_Aarnes |language=Norwegian | accessdate=24 October 2010 }}</ref> and published a series of handbooks on journalism.<ref name=nbl/>
As a proponent for the [[Nynorsk]] language he founded the news agency Norsk Pressekontor in 1918.<ref name=nbl/> He founded the magazine ''[[Nynorsk Vekeblad]]'' in 1933.<ref name=nab/> He started the comic series ''[[Vangsgutane]]'' in ''Nynorsk Vekeblad'' as a local alternative to ''[[The Katzenjammer Kids]]'', with text by [[Leif Halse]] and drawn by [[Jens R. Nilssen]].<ref name=snl-vangsgutane>{{cite encyclopedia |title=Vangsgutane |encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]] |publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget |location=Oslo |url=http://www.snl.no/Vangsgutane |language=Norwegian | accessdate=28 October 2010 }}</ref> He was member of the board of [[Det Norske Teatret]] from 1935 to 1940,<ref name=dnt>{{cite book |title=Det Norske Teatret. Femti år 1913–1963 |year=1963 |editor=[[Nils Sletbak|Sletbak, Nils]] |language=Norwegian|publisher=Det Norske Samlaget |location=Oslo |page=462}}</ref> and founded the publishing house [[Fonna Forlag]] in 1940. He was initiator of the Nynorsk encyclopedia ''[[Norsk Allkunnebok]]'', which was published between 1948 and 1966.<ref name=nbl/> He was active in the organization [[Noregs Mållag]], and helped the establishing of several local chapters in the 1950s.<ref name=nab/>
