{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}} {{Infobox writer | name = Josep Carles Laínez | image = | caption = | birth_date = 1970 | birth_place = [[Valencia, Spain|Valencia]], [[Valencia province]], Valencian Community, Spain | death_date = | death_place = | spouse = | children = | occupation = Writer | signature = | movement = [[Asturian language literature]], [[Aragonese language literature]] }} '''Josep Carles Laínez''' (born 1970) is a Spanish writer who lives in [[Valencia, Spain]] and [[Encamp]], Andorra. A graduate of the [[University of Valencia]] in Catalan and Spanish Philology and Audio-visual Communication, his main interest is in European minority languages,<ref>http://magnaeuropa.blogspot.com/2007/04/la-judeofobia-solidaria.html magna Europa</ref> and he has published original books and/or articles in [[Catalan language|Catalan]], English, Spanish, [[Occitan]], [[Aragonese language|Aragonese]] and [[Asturian language|Asturian]]. He is currently the Editor-in-chief of the literary-philosophical quarterly journal ''Debats''.
In his book of poetry ''Música junto al río'' (''Music by the River'', 2001), he uses a dialectal Valencian-Aragonese from the region of his parents. His book ''La piedra ente la ñeve'' (''The Stone in the Snow'', 2010) is notable as the first Latter-day Saint-related book published in Asturian and the first to use the [[Deseret alphabet]] for a language other than English.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.motleyvision.org/2010/la-piedra-ente-la-neve/ |title=La Piedra Ente La Ñeve |author=[[Kent Larsen]] |date= 9 November 2010|work= [[A Motley Vision]] |publisher= |accessdate=15 November 2010}}</ref> He has also published a translation of aphorisms from the Asturian into the Spanish language (''Ene marginalia'', 2003). {{citation needed|date=June 2012}}
Laínez is a columnist for the Andorran newspaper ''[[El Periòdic d'Andorra]]'', and has been a visiting professor at the [[National Autonomous University of Mexico]], [[University of Puerto Rico]], [[Hofstra University]] of New York and [[Komazawa University]] of Tokyo.
