{{distinguish|Kota language (Gabon)|Kota language (Central African Republic)}} {{Infobox language |name=Kota |nativename=''Kō mānt'' |states=[[India]] |ethnicity=[[Kota people (India)|Kotas]] |region=[[Nilgiris district|Nilgiri Hills]] |speakers=930 <!--1,400 (2001 census?) appears w pop. date <ref name=e17>{{e17|kfe}}</ref> --> |date=2001 census |ref=e18 |familycolor=Dravidian |fam2=[[Southern Dravidian languages|Southern]] |fam3=[[Tamil–Kannada languages|Tamil–Kannada]] |fam4=[[Tamil–Kodagu languages|Tamil–Kodagu]] |fam5=[[Toda–Kota languages|Toda–Kota]] |iso3=kfe |glotto=kota1263 |glottorefname=Kota (India) |notice=Indic }} '''Kota''' is a language of the [[Dravidian languages|Dravidian language family]] with about 9000 native speakers in the [[Nilgiri hills]] of [[Tamil Nadu]] state, [[India]]. It is spoken mainly by the tribal [[Kota people (India)|Kota people]]. In the late 19th century, the native speaking population was about 1,100.<ref>Caldwell, Robert. 1875. A Comparative Grammar of the Dravidian Or South-Indian Family of Languages. London: Trübner & Company</ref> In 1990, the population was only 930, out of an ethnic population of perhaps 1,400, despite the great increase in the population of the area.<ref name=e18/> The language is 'critically endangered' due to the greater social status of neighbouring languages.<ref>Prema, S. n.d. "Status of Dravidian Tribal Languages in Kerala" University of Kerala</ref> The Kota language may have originated from [[Old Kannada]] and is closely related to [[Toda language|Toda]]. The Kota population is about 2500. The origin of the name Kota is derived from the Dravida root word 'Ko' meaning Mountain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hellomyexpert.com/breekschatter/summer2012/2012/06/30/the-kotas-jamuna-raju-89/|title=The Kota Tribes of Nilgiris|last=Raju|first=Jamuna|date=30 June 2012|website=Breeks Chatter}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=yhXRDSgBuL0C&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=kota&f=false|title=History of Kannada Language|last=Narasimhacharya|first=R.|publisher=Asian Educational Services|year=1990|isbn=9788120605596|location=New Delhi, Madras|pages=37}}</ref>
==Phonology== {|class="wikitable" style="text-align:center" |+[[Consonant]]s<ref>{{cite book|last=Krishnamurti|first=Bhadriraju|title=The Dravidian languages|year=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|isbn=978-0-511-06037-3|pages=53|edition=null}}</ref> |- !colspan=2| ![[Labial consonant|Labial]] ![[Dental consonant|Dental]] ![[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ![[Retroflex consonant|Retroflex]] ![[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ![[Velar consonant|Velar]] |- !rowspan=2| [[Plosive consonant|Plosive]] !{{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}} | {{IPA|p}} || {{IPA|t̪}} || {{IPA|t}} || {{IPA|ʈ}} || {{IPA|c}} ({{IPA|t͡ʃ}}) || {{IPA|k}} |- !{{small|[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}} | {{IPA|b}} || {{IPA|d̪}} || {{IPA|d}} || {{IPA|ɖ}} || {{IPA|ɟ}} ({{IPA|d͡ʒ}}) || {{IPA|ɡ}} |- !colspan=2| [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] | {{IPA|m}} || {{IPA|n̪}} || || {{IPA|ɳ}} || {{IPA|ɲ}} || |- !rowspan=2| [[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] !{{small|[[central consonant|central]]}} | {{IPA|ʋ}} || || || || {{IPA|j}} || |- !{{small|[[lateral consonant|lateral]]}} | || || {{IPA|l}} || {{IPA|ɭ}} || || |- !colspan=2| [[Flap consonant|Tap]] | || || {{IPA|ɾ}} || {{IPA|ɽ}} || || |- !colspan=2| [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] | || || {{IPA|s}} || || || |}
[{{IPA|s}}] and [{{IPA|z}}] occur in free variation with /{{IPA|c}} ({{IPA|t͡ʃ}})/ and /{{IPA|ɟ}} ({{IPA|d͡ʒ}})/. [{{IPA|ʂ}}] occurs as an allophone of /{{IPA|s}}/ before retroflexes.
